## Why one file per diagram

`node-map.puml` answers **"what nodes exist and which layer do they sit in"**. The six `data-flow-*.puml` files answer **"what data moves through the system on which path"**.

`data-flow-overview.puml` is the layer-grain entry point. The five detail files each zoom into one slice of the overview and show actual nodes + topic names + rates. Each canvas stays under 10 arrows with no crossings.

One file per diagram (instead of multi-page) so:
- Each renders independently ‚Äî no need to extract a specific page.
- Each can be embedded directly in markdown via image link (as done above).
- Editing one diagram doesn't touch the others' git history.

## Rendering

\`\`\`bash
plantuml -tsvg *.puml
plantuml -tsvg data-flow-overview.puml   # just one
plantuml -tpng *.puml                     # PNG for slides
\`\`\`

After editing any `.puml`, re-run `plantuml -tsvg <file>.puml` and commit the regenerated `.svg` so the embedded previews above stay in sync.

## Reading order

1. **Node map** ‚Äî orient yourself in the layer geography.
2. **Data-flow overview** ‚Äî see the layer-to-layer flows.
3. Pick the **detail diagram** matching whatever you're touching.

The detail diagrams are *zoom-ins* on one slice of the overview ‚Äî go to the overview first, then drill in.

Each per-node spec under [`../nodes/`](../nodes/) cross-references the relevant detail diagram.
